The European "Green Deal"
NEW YORK – Europe has done it.
The "green deal for Europe" announced by the European Commission is, to date, the first comprehensive sustainable development plan decided by a major region of the planet.
It has therefore become a reference point for the world – a guide for the transition to a prosperous, socially inclusive, and ecologically sustainable economy, the first agenda, for everyone's use, to achieve this.
Of course, the task awaiting Europeans is impressive.
Even the reading of the documents just made public reveals: a lavish array of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy, a large number of involved and related subjects, ranging from energy to transport, from food to industry.
Its critics will mock European bureaucracy.
But it is bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense of the term: it is rational.
Sustainable development goals are clearly stated, targets are defined based on goals subject to a schedule, and programs and procedures are adapted to the targets.
Overall, the stated ambition is to achieve « carbon neutrality » (zero net emissions of greenhouse gases) by 2050, to establish a circular economy that ends destructive pollution from plastics and other petrochemical derivatives, pesticides, and toxic waste, and to establish a « farm-to-table » food system that does not kill people by making them eat overly processed industrial products, nor kill the land with unsustainable agricultural practices.
And the European Commission understands that the method to achieve this must rely on the citizens themselves.
Again, critics will see public consultations as mere noise and empty dreams.
But go tell the useless chatter to President Emmanuel Macron of France, who has faced over a year of demonstrations turning into riots, or to President Sebastián Piñera of Chile, whose country suddenly rose up this autumn after a slight increase in subway ticket prices.
Macron and Piñera are both convinced of the necessity of ecological change.
Both have committed to carbon neutrality in their countries by 2050.
And both are desperately trying to organize or structure a public consultation, but only after the fact.
American neoliberal enthusiasts will once again mock and claim that the « market » knows how to deal with climate change.
But one only needs to look at today’s United States.
If neoliberalism treats the planet as it has treated American infrastructure, we all have cause for concern.
Arriving at an airport in the United States means having to endure elevators, escalators, shuttle buses that are out of order, taxis that don’t arrive, nonexistent rail connections, highways in such poor condition that they can’t be used, replaced by detours.
The reason for these malfunctions is simple: corruption.
Every American electoral cycle now costs $8 billion, if not more, and is funded by billionaires, large oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobby, and interest groups determined to lower taxes and protect the status quo at all costs.
Market solutions are a farce when politics is subject to all the influences that emanate from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Deal shows a government as it should be, and not a government subordinate to corporate interests.
The European Green Deal actually demonstrates the success of European social democracy (in its operational sense, not strictly partisan).
An economy that combines markets, state regulatory power, the public sector, and civil society will pursue a mixed strategy: public objectives, public investment in infrastructure, private investment in industrial transformation, research and development missions based on public-private partnerships, and an informed population.
In fact, it is an industrial policy at its most sophisticated level.
(I have recently outlined, in broad strokes, what a socially democratic Green New Deal strategy would look like for the United States.)
We have reasons to be optimistic.
The most important point is that the advanced technologies that will enable the creation of a decarbonized, resource-efficient, and therefore ecologically sustainable advanced economy exist, at the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
By combining renewable energy, digital technologies, cutting-edge materials, and the collaborative economy in transport or other infrastructure, we can decarbonize the energy system, move toward a circular economy, and drastically reduce the flow of primary resources.
But to do this, we must overcome three major challenges.
The first is to overcome the interests that seek to maintain the status quo.
Large oil companies will have to absorb losses, but workers in the sector and mining regions should receive compensation, in the form of income support, retraining through education, and other public aid.
The European plan rightly claims a « just transition ».
The second challenge is that of financing.
The European Union, like other regions of the world, will have to redirect a relatively small portion of its production, from 1% to 2%, towards the green economy, particularly in the areas of new infrastructure, public procurement, research and development, the renewal of industrial equipment, etc. Financing will come from the private sector, as well as from public budgets.
The European Union must stand up to ideologues who oppose an increase in EU spending.
Facts must be taken into account.
The last major challenge is diplomatic.
Europe accounts for approximately 9.1 % of global carbon dioxide emissions, while China's share is 30 % and that of the United States is 14 %.
Even if Europe manages to implement its Green Deal in its entirety, it will be in vain if other regions of the world do not join it in its fight.
European leaders therefore rightly consider that diplomacy is fundamental to the success of the Green Deal.
Take the example of China.
After decades of rapid growth, which eliminated mass poverty, China has become the world's top CO2 emitter (although its per capita emissions remain half those of the United States).
China, alone, will determine the future of global climate.
On the one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if it does not make enough efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they face the dangers of the unfortunate cold war launched by America.
Hardliners within the government and Chinese coal lobbies resist decarbonization, especially under pressure from the United States, since Trump himself rejects it.
European diplomacy can make a difference if it refuses to subscribe to America's insidious measures to hinder China and instead proposes to China a positive and unambiguous partnership: working together to establish infrastructure, sustainable development, and technology in Eurasia, within the framework of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to Europe's.
A partnership of this kind would be of immense benefit to Europe, China, and the dozen of Eurasian countries that lie between them, not to mention the world as a whole.
The European Union has taken a historic step with its ambitious, mobilizing, and achievable plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful signal of hope in a world of uncertainties and instability.
